 tablets 101?</span><hr size=1> I've been kicking around the idea of finally shelling out the cash for a Wacom tablet. I got the chance to play around with one a few weeks ago and I really enjoyed it. Although it turns out that it was a the Cintiq model, which I just found out costs $1,899 to $3,499. The only type of tablet which I've used was the Cintiq. This is of course far more than I want to invest, so I was looking at the Intuos2, but one thing I am having a hard time figuring out is what type of screen it has, theres no actual pictures of a image being displayed on the tablet on the website, so I was wondering if these tablets require you to sort of draw by looking at your monitor and not the tablet? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=mechawashu>mechawashu</A> at: 8/19/02 11:11:30 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/umadadric.showPublicProfile?language=EN>madadric</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://wind.prohosting.com/madadric/madadric-avatar.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/20/02 12:22:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4260.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.livejournal.com/userpic/1709922 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wacom tablets 101?</span><hr size=1> that's right. the intuos2 and graphire2 tablets don't have a display, you hafta look at the monitor.<br>
<br>
i recently bought a graphire2, and while at first i was disoriented, i quickly got used to it, and i think, the Intuos2 that you were looking at is a step up from the graphire2, it has a few more extras, and more range in the pressure.<br>
<br>
