madadric@hotmail.com</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=browndog>BrownDog</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/20/02 12:23:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4260.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Wa...</span><hr size=1> It doesn't have a screen, its just a pressure sensitive pad. You draw on the tablet and look at your monitor. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/urayne69.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rayne69</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/20/02 11:07:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4260.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wa...</span><hr size=1> you may think at first it's hard to look at the screen while drawing, Cging.  But in fact if you ever get a chance to try it, you'll find it's very easy and simple to use.  you can draw as you normally can, i doubted this at first, but when i got the graphire2 i was satisfied that i bought it after all! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uqixiang.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Qixiang</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/20/02 11:35:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4260.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re</span><hr size=1> I find it useful to put the tablet directly in front of me like a sketch pad. Since I find it hard to draw vertical lines when it's put on the side. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uchikin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Chikin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/20/02 11:49:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4260.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.buttonpusher.net/kindamanga/dogtopus.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re</span><hr size=1> &quot;It doesn't have a screen, its just a pressure sensitive pad. You draw on the tablet and look at your monitor.&quot; Yup. :) But the pen's pressure sensitive, not the pad. Heehee, sorry, I'm just being retentive. XD Haha! But yeah, you can actually hold the pen close to the tablet (but not touching), and push down on the eraser on the back and draw with that. It's weird, and not useful for anything, but fun for about a minute. :D<br>
<br>
But yeah, you do get used to it. I use a Graphire 2 too, and I find that so long as you keep the tablet kinda straight it's easy to draw where you want. And programs such as OpenCanvas allow you to twist the onscreen canvas around too, just in case you can't get the angle. It becomes intuitive after an hour or so, it's cool. :) <p><div align="center">
